threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a sophisticated kernel-mode rootkit designed for low-level network interception and stealth. It employs classic rootkit techniques to hide its presence by unlinking its DriverObject and clearing pointers in the system's device and driver directories (sub_1400011cc). It intercepts network traffic by registering an NDIS protocol driver and hooking the 'TCPIP' binding to redirect packet handling to internal routines (sub_140001aa4). The driver performs deep packet inspection of IPv4/TCP traffic (sub_140002cdc), recalculates checksums after potential modification, and provides a command-and-control (C2) interface by hijacking the dispatch routine of '\Device\Null' (sub_140002564). Relevant IOCs include the use of the synchronization event '\BaseNamedObjects\{75F09225-CD50-460B-BF90-5743B8404D73}' and NDIS hooking of the 'TCPIP' protocol driver.
